    "faqid": "1",
    "section": "51100",
    "faq":
        "<div><strong>How do I write a Summary section?<\/strong><\/div><div>The summary should be 3-5 sentences in paragraph form. It should capture your career history and the most valuable skills and experience you offer. It&rsquo;s the first thing a potential employer sees, so it&rsquo;s your chance to sell yourself quickly. Here are some things to include in a Summary Statement:<\/div><ol><li>Your current field, years of experience and career focus<\/li><li>The most relevant part of your background for the position you are applying for.<\/li><li>The most impressive result you&rsquo;ve achieved in your career<\/li><li>What you offer the potential employer.<\/li><\/ol><div>Example: &ldquo;Bi-lingual Customer Service Manager with 10 years experience in a high-volume call centre. Energetic and organized team lead with a history of successful on-boarding of regional support teams. Achieved 10% reduction in refund requests and 15% increase in sales over a 2-year period. Seeking a position in a company expanding its support operations into English-speaking countries.&rdquo;<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><div><strong>Can I use &ldquo;I&rdquo; in my resume?<\/strong><\/div><\/div><div>&quot;I,&quot; &quot;me,&quot; or &quot;my&quot; should never be used in a resume. &ldquo;I&rdquo; may be used in a cover letter, but sparingly. Example: Correct: &ldquo;Managed 4 team members&rdquo;. Incorrect: &ldquo;I managed 4 team members&quot;<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><div><strong>I&rsquo;m a student and don&rsquo;t have much work experience. What goes in the Summary Statement?<\/strong><\/div><\/div><div>There&rsquo;s nothing wrong with stating up-front where you are in your education or career.&nbsp; If you&rsquo;re a student or recent graduate, you may want to focus on skills and school accomplishments instead of your work history.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>Do I need to include a summary?<\/strong><\/div><div>We recommend always having a summary on the top of your resume. Consider it your &ldquo;elevator pitch,&rdquo; or what you would say if you had 30 seconds to sell yourself for a job. If your summary doesn&rsquo;t sound convincing, the hiring manager may not read further.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>How do I write a summary if I&rsquo;m applying to several different types of jobs?<\/strong><\/div><div>We recommend adjusting your resume to each job you are targeting. Review the job description, look at your background, and pull keywords from the job description and incorporate them into your resume examples. Show them you are the perfect fit.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>I don&rsquo;t have much work experience. What goes in the Summary Statement?<\/strong><\/div><div>There&rsquo;s nothing wrong with stating up-front where you are in your education and career. If you&rsquo;re a student and don&rsquo;t have a lot of work experience, your Summary Statement should focus on your most compelling skills and attributes, whether gained on the job or through your education.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>Where does Career Objective go?<\/strong><\/div><div>Including a &ldquo;Career Objective&rdquo; section is no longer considered a best practice. You may include a statement of the type of work you are seeking in the Summary section but it isn&rsquo;t necessary. We recommend including a Career Objective in your cover letter.<\/div>",
    "dateCreated": "2017-02-19 10:37:47",
    "status": "1"
  },
  {
    "faqid": "6",
    "section": "51104",
    "faq":
        "<div><div><strong>How do I format my work experience?<\/strong><\/div><\/div><div>We recommend listing 3-5 bulleted examples under each position in a standard resume format. Each bullet point should be a complete sentence, about one line in length.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>How many years of work history should I include?<\/strong><\/div><div>For a standard chronological resume, we recommend going into detail for the past 10-15 years of your work history. Include more examples for the most recent positions and fewer for older ones. For jobs held more than 15 years ago, list only job title, employer, and location.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>In what order do I list my jobs?<\/strong><\/div><div>Use reverse chronological order; show the most recent first and work backwards to the earliest position.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>I am returning to the workforce.&nbsp; How do I include my time off work?<\/strong><\/div><div>For people who have taken a break from the workforce, we recommend a functional or hybrid resume format. These formats present your experience based on your skills rather than in chronological order.&nbsp; Your resume should be focused on what you are bringing to the employer, and less focused on time you were not in the workforce. Your cover letter is the best place to explicitly address the time period you were off the workforce due to family concerns, health issues, or other factors.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>What if I don&#39;t have any work experience?<\/strong><\/div><div>List any volunteer, scholastic or community experience that you have. Be specific about what you participated in and your accomplishments. If you have relevant internship experience, list it under your work experience section.&nbsp;<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>Do I need to include dates for my work history?<\/strong><\/div><div>Yes, you should include starting and ending dates for each employer listed in the work history section.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s best to show both months and years. If you decide to show only years, a discerning hiring manager may wonder why you aren&rsquo;t providing more detail. Once you choose a format, stick to it and stay consistent throughout the resume.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><div><strong>What is Employer location?<\/strong><\/div><\/div><div>Employer location means the city and state where you worked for the Employer. In a standard resume, it&rsquo;s not necessary to include a street name or building number.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>What does &ldquo;Employer&rdquo; mean?<\/strong><\/div><div>Employer refers to the name of the organization or company where you worked. If you were employed by an individual instead of an organization or company, use that person&rsquo;s full name as the Employer.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>I worked for a temporary agency. How do I list that experience?<\/strong><\/div><div>Temporary work can be treated in the same way as other work history. List the agency as the employer, followed by the location and the dates of employment. Use an appropriate title, such as &ldquo;Inventory Clerk,&rdquo; &ldquo;Administrative Support,&rdquo; or other general position title.<\/div>",
    "dateCreated": "2017-02-19 10:41:35",
    "status": "1"
  },
  {
    "faqid": "7",
    "section": "51106",
    "faq":
        "<div><strong>What is Internship?<\/strong><\/div><div>Internship is an on-the-job training opportunity provided to students while they are pursuing and graduate or post graduate degree. In other words it offers students a hands-on opportunity to work in their desired field. They learn how their course of study applies to the real world and build valuable experience that makes them stronger candidates for jobs after graduation.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>Do I need to include dates for my internship?<\/strong><\/div><div>Yes, you should include starting and ending dates for each employer listed in the work history section.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s best to show both months and years. If you decide to show only years, a discerning hiring manager may wonder why you aren&rsquo;t providing more detail.<\/div>",
    "dateCreated": "2017-02-19 11:35:20",
    "status": "1"
  },
  {
    "faqid": "9",
    "section": "51108",
    "faq":
        "<div><div><strong>What is professional qualification?<\/strong><\/div><\/div><div>Professional qualifications are vocational qualifications, often involving an element of practical training. Usually, they are linked with a specific industry and are designed to help you improve and develop relevant skills for a particular career path. For example: Chartered Accountant.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>Do I include ALL my professional degrees?<\/strong><\/div><div>Yes you should disclose all the professional degrees held by you.<\/div><div><strong>&nbsp;<\/strong><\/div><div><strong>Should I include my grades?<\/strong><\/div><div>If you have impressive grade, you may include it. It is not necessary unless an employer requests it.<\/div>",
    "dateCreated": "2017-02-19 11:37:16",
    "status": "1"
  },
  {
    "faqid": "8",
    "section": "51109",
    "faq":
        "<div><div><strong>Do I include ALL my education?<\/strong><\/div><\/div><div>If you have an extensive educational history, keep the section brief and easy to read.&nbsp; Don&#39;t use more than two lines for each degree. It&rsquo;s not necessary to provide a long list of coursework or explanations.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>Do I include my high school education?<\/strong><\/div><div>If high school is your highest degree, you should include your high school degree information.&nbsp; You may remove high school information and use your current school once you begin at a new academic institution or professional school.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><div><strong>Can I list certifications and other classes in the Education section?<\/strong><\/div><div>The Education section generally includes only degrees. Certifications should be mentioned in Certifications section.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>Should I list classes I&rsquo;ve taken?<\/strong><\/div><div>If you don&rsquo;t have much work experience, then coursework can supplement your resume. But only mention coursework relevant to your targeted jobs. Include no more than four or five relevant courses. Special projects can also be listed.<\/div><\/div>",
    "dateCreated": "2017-02-19 11:35:34",
    "status": "1"
  },
  {
    "faqid": "10",
    "section": "51110",
    "faq":
        "<div><div><strong>Do I include ALL the Certification Courses undertaken by me?<\/strong><\/div><\/div><div>Show only those certifications which are relevant to the desired job. Include no more than five most recent rectifications. If you have more than five certifications let the employer know that additional information is available upon request.<\/div>",
    "dateCreated": "2017-02-19 11:39:28",
    "status": "1"
  },
  {
    "faqid": "11",
    "section": "51113",
    "faq":
        "<div><div><strong>Do I include patents applied for but approval pending?<\/strong><\/div><\/div><div>Yes add details about those patents for which you have applied for but approval is yet pending because it will be a concrete way of showing that you are innovative and can come up with good solutions that are deserving of a patent. Also, most of the companies while hiring specifically ask to a sign a document regarding intellectual property right. Hence it is wise to disclose pending patents in your resume.<\/div>",
    "dateCreated": "2017-02-19 11:40:36",
    "status": "1"
  },
  {
    "faqid": "12",
    "section": "51116",
    "faq":
        "<div><div><strong>What is a professional Forum?<\/strong><\/div><\/div><div>A professional organization is a body whose primary objective is to promote a particular profession, the interests of individuals engaged in that profession and public interest. &quot;Institute of Chartered Accountants of India&quot;, &quot;ICTACEM&quot;, &quot;Rotary Wing Society of India&quot;, etc are some professional organisations in India.<\/div>",
    "dateCreated": "2017-02-19 11:41:51",
    "status": "1"
  },
  {
    "faqid": "13",
    "section": "51118",
    "faq":
        "<div><div><strong>Which skills should I list?<\/strong><br \/>We recommend you tailor each resume to each job you are applying for so you can match your skills to the employer&rsquo;s needs. Take a look at job descriptions for similar positions to choose which skills to highlight.<\/div><\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>How do I write skills?<\/strong><br \/>This section is meant to be quick and easy to review. Use 2- to 3-word phrases without periods. If something needs a longer description add it to Work History.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>How many skills should I include?<\/strong><br \/>3 - 5 skills. The Skills section should list the skills most relevant to your targeted job. If you have more than 5, list the most important in the Skills section, and include the others into your Work History section.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>Where do I list computer or technical skills?<\/strong><br \/>They should be reflected in &ldquo;Technical Skills&rdquo; section.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>Where do I include certifications?<\/strong><br \/>They should be reflected in Certification section.&nbsp;<\/div>",
    "dateCreated": "2017-02-19 11:44:09",
    "status": "1"
  },
  {
    "faqid": "14",
    "section": "51124",
    "faq":
        "<div><div><strong>What are the different sections of a cover letter?<\/strong><br \/>Our Cover Letter Builder will guide you through creating all sections necessary in a well-written cover letter:<\/div><\/div><ul><li>Recipient: Who is going to receive your letter, along with his or her contact information.<\/li><li>Subject Line: The topic of your letter, which should reference the job you&rsquo;re applying to.<\/li><li>Greeting: A professional salutation addressing your reader.<\/li><li>Introduction: An attention-grabbing introduction to who you are and what unique advantages you offer.<\/li><li>Letter Body: The primary content of your letter, and your chance to outline what you have to offer in relation to the employer&rsquo;s needs.<\/li><li>Call to Action: A chance to draw the reader&rsquo;s attention to your resume, offer instruction on how to best contact you, and suggest an in-person interview regarding the position.<\/li><li>Closer: A short and simple sign-off to your letter.<\/li><\/ul><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>Is it too pushy to ask for an interview in a cover letter?<\/strong><br \/>Not at all. If you&rsquo;re using this letter to respond to a job posting, the recipient expects that you&rsquo;ll want to interview for the position at hand and the letter is your chance to explain why they should invite you to do so.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>How long should my cover letter be?<\/strong><br \/>We know it&rsquo;s tempting to tell your whole story in your cover letter, but remember this document is just a sales pitch for your resume.&nbsp; You don&rsquo;t need to include your entire history. Three short paragraphs (2-3 sentences each) highlighting your experience as it specifically relates to the job at hand will be sufficient.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/div><div>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>What are some examples of &ldquo;job-related skills and accomplishments&rdquo;?<\/strong><br \/>In a cover letter, you generally want to highlight one or two of your most significant professional successes. The more specific you can be, the better, and including numbers will help your cause. Examples: &ldquo;supervised 5 employees&rdquo;; &ldquo;increased sales by 17% in 6 months&rdquo;; &ldquo;developed a marketing plan that led an increase of 20,000 social media hits&rdquo;, etc.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/div><div>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>Should I include my references?<\/strong><br \/>Only if the job posting specifically requests that you do so. References are usually requested and checked toward the end of the hiring process.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><div><strong>I don&rsquo;t have a contact name for the position I&rsquo;m targeting. Who should I address my cover letter to?<\/strong><\/div><\/div><div>While having a name at the company is best, if you don&rsquo;t have a contact to whom you can address your letter, directing it to &ldquo;Hiring Manager&rdquo; is acceptable. Avoid general addresses such as &ldquo;To whom it may concern,&rdquo; or &ldquo;Dear Sir or Madam,&rdquo; and always keep your salutation gender-neutral.<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div><div><strong>How many cover letters should I create?<\/strong><\/div><div>While it is certainly tempting to use the same letter for every job you apply to, we strongly recommend taking the time to create a new version of your letter for every potential job target. Each letter you send should be specifically tailored to the job description, incorporating words and phrases used by the company.&nbsp; A little extra work up front will help get your foot in the door faster, shortening your job search in the long run!<\/div><div>&nbsp;<\/div>",
    "dateCreated": "2017-02-19 12:26:01",
    "status": "1"
  }
];

